\begin{theorem}
A method
\[
\begin{pmatrix}
A & U \\
B & V
\end{pmatrix},
\]
has order and stage order $p$ if and only if there exists a function
\[
\varphi : \mathbb{C} \to \mathbb{C}^{r},
\]
analytic in a neighbourhood of $0$, such that
\begin{align}
\exp(cz) &= zA \exp(cz) + U \varphi(z) + O(z^{p+1}), \label{eq:541a} \\
\exp(z)\varphi(z) &= zB \exp(cz) + V \varphi(z) + O(z^{p+1}), \label{eq:541b}
\end{align}
where $\exp(cz)$ denotes the vector in $\mathbb{C}^{s}$ for which component $i$ is equal to $\exp(c_i z)$.
\end{theorem}

context_latex:
\paragraph{Context}
The theorem concerns DIMSIM methods (diagonally implicit multistage integration methods) with equal order and stage order $p$. The method is represented by a partitioned matrix with blocks $A$, $U$, $B$, $V$, where $A$ is typically diagonal for parallel evaluation. The context discusses types of DIMSIM methods based on $\lambda$ (diagonal element of $A$) for stiff/non-stiff problems.

Variables: $p$: order and stage order; $q$: order and stage order (here $p = q$); $r$: dimension of the vector $\phi(z)$; $s$: number of stages; $A$, $U$, $B$, $V$: coefficient matrices; $c$: vector of abscissae $c_i$.
